    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the goblin misstep! Now, when the cold air hits the warm air, it's because cold air is denser than warm air. Imagine a bunch of heavy, cold goblin rocks pushing down on a pile of fluffy, warm goblin pillows. The pillows (warm air) are lighter and start to rise above the rocks (cold air). This happens because cold air sinks and warm air rises due to differences in density. The rising warm air can cool down, condense, and form clouds, which often leads to precipitation. It's like the warm goblins are saying goodbye and heading up to the sky, while the cold goblins stay down below.",
